<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<databaseChangeLog
    xmlns="http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog"
    xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog
    http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog/dbchangelog-3.8.xsd">

    <!--
        #3711 — give the @Version / "last updated" columns a DB-level DEFAULT.

        OE has two entity-mapping vintages, so the optimistic-lock @Version column
        exists under TWO names:
          * annotation entities (BaseObject): @Version @Column(name="last_updated")
          * legacy *.hbm.xml entities (UnitOfMeasure, TypeOfSample, SiteInformation,
            ResultLimits, … — 80+ mappings): <version column="LASTUPDATED"/>  →  lastupdated
        These columns were created NULLABLE with no default. Hibernate normally
        supplies the value on insert, so production mostly worked — but any insert
        that OMITS the column lands a NULL version, most importantly the DBUnit test
        fixtures. The first UPDATE of such a row then emits "... WHERE <col> = NULL",
        matches 0 rows, and throws StaleStateException (surfaced by the per-test
        rollback work in #3711).

        Fix it where the invariant belongs — the schema — by giving every last-updated
        timestamp column (BOTH spellings) DEFAULT now(). A column default only applies
        when the INSERT omits the column, which is exactly the fixture / seed-SQL case;
        it does NOT interfere with Hibernate, which sets the value explicitly.

        Why DEFAULT and NOT "NOT NULL": several legacy *.hbm.xml entities' Hibernate
        inserts pass an EXPLICIT NULL for the version column (e.g. observation_history_type,
        patient_type) — a pre-existing quirk of those mappings. A DEFAULT cannot override
        an explicit NULL, and a NOT NULL constraint would reject those inserts. Enforcing
        NOT NULL would therefore require also fixing every such insert path to seed the
        version — a large, separate change across the legacy mappings. This changeset
        deliberately fixes only the actual failure (NULL versions from column-omitting
        inserts) and leaves NOT NULL enforcement + the lastupdated→last_updated rename
        (à la liquibase/qc/006) as separate hygiene.

        The block is self-guarding and idempotent: it backfills existing NULLs (so any
        already-persisted row is safe to update) and adds a default only where one is
        missing (never clobbering a deliberate default).
    -->
    <changeSet id="044-version-column-default-now" author="openelisglobal" runInTransaction="true">
        <sql splitStatements="false" stripComments="false"><![CDATA[
DO $$
DECLARE
    r record;
BEGIN
    FOR r IN
        SELECT c.table_name, c.column_name, c.column_default
        FROM information_schema.columns c
        JOIN information_schema.tables t
            ON t.table_schema = c.table_schema AND t.table_name = c.table_name
        WHERE c.table_schema = 'clinlims'
            AND c.column_name IN ('last_updated', 'lastupdated')
            AND t.table_type = 'BASE TABLE'
    LOOP
        -- Defuse any already-persisted NULL versions so their next UPDATE won't fail.
        EXECUTE format('UPDATE clinlims.%I SET %I = now() WHERE %I IS NULL',
            r.table_name, r.column_name, r.column_name);
        -- Supply a default only where one is missing (do not clobber an existing default).
        IF r.column_default IS NULL THEN
            EXECUTE format('ALTER TABLE clinlims.%I ALTER COLUMN %I SET DEFAULT now()',
                r.table_name, r.column_name);
        END IF;
    END LOOP;
END $$;
        ]]></sql>
    </changeSet>

</databaseChangeLog>
